al health services. The research has important clinical and policy implications, and will be of key interest to those in psychology and the helping professions as well as to people in recovery and their families.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Mental Health.2bisacsh1 aO’Connell, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSells, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStaeheli, Martha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStrauss, John S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081471942840uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814785355.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814785355423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814785355/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MDPM  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MDPM  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK